I"¾<p>The brain can be seen as a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/continuous-state-dynamical-systems-share-a-common-structure">continuous-state continuous-time dynamical system</a>. Its <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dynamical-systems-have-a-certain-anatomy">state space</a> is defined as the space of all possible <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/context-disambiguates-observed-neural-activity">neural activity configurations</a>. Its autonomous <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dynamical-systems-have-a-certain-anatomy">transition function</a> is based on internal wiring. <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/phenomenal-space-is-adaptive">Trajectories are thought patterns</a>. The input function is <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/perception-is-context-dependent">perception</a>, and takes into account both the internal and external states. Finally, the output function is motor action.</p>
